\chapter{Appendix C --- Paper-to-Chapter Cross-Reference}
\label{app:C}

\section{C.1 Appendix Overview}

This appendix assigns every publication-grade Event Density paper to exactly one chapter of the monograph. The assignment is structural rather than thematic: each paper is placed at the chapter where its content is load-bearing, even when the paper's results are referenced in later chapters. Where a paper covers material spanning multiple chapters (notably the NS Synthesis Paper with its Appendices C, D, and E), the main paper is assigned to its anchoring chapter and each appendix is assigned to the chapter for which it is structurally definitive.

The cross-reference is consistent with Appendix A (theorem provenance map): every canonical-source path cited in Appendix A appears here under the chapter to which the source paper is assigned. It is consistent with Appendix B (notation glossary): every symbol defined in Appendix B has its canonical definition in a paper assigned here. It is consistent with Appendix D (substrate constants): every constant defined in Appendix D has its derivation or empirical anchor in a paper assigned here. Repository paths are stated relative to the repository root \texttt{event-density/}, exactly as in the chapter sources.

\bigskip\hrule\bigskip

\section{C.2 Part I — Substrate Foundations}

\subsection{Chapter 1 — The Substrate Ontology (P1–P13)}

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{\texttt{papers/Event\_Density\_Ontology\_and\_Axioms/}} — Canonical inventory of the thirteen substrate primitives and the axiomatic structure of the program. Every later result is reachable from a subset of P1–P13 plus mathematical structure.
\item \textbf{\texttt{papers/Foundations\_of\_Event\_Density/}} — Companion foundations collection: discusses the ontological commitments behind each primitive, the substrate-locality conditions, and the boundary between substrate ontology and emergent continuum physics.
\item \textbf{\texttt{papers/ED\_One\_Substrate\_Three\_Domains/}} — Program-overview / orientation context. Used in Chapter 1 only as a reading aid for situating the substrate ontology within the program's three-domain organization (substrate, continuum, gravity).
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Chapter 2 — Load-Bearing Invariants}

\begin{itemize}
